{"title_page": "List of countries with overseas military bases", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThis is a '''list of countries with overseas [[military base]]s'''.\n\n{{TOCright|80}}\n\n==Background==\nThe establishment of military bases abroad enables a country to [[Power projection|project power]], e.g. to conduct [[expeditionary warfare]], and thereby influence events abroad. Depending on their size and infrastructure, they can be used as [[staging area]]s or for logistical, communications and intelligence support. Many conflicts throughout modern history have resulted in overseas military bases being established in large numbers by [[world power]]s and the existence of bases abroad has served countries having them in achieving political and military goals. The [[British Empire]] and other colonial powers established overseas military bases in many of their colonies during the [[First World War|First]] and [[Second World War]]s, where useful, and actively sought rights to facilities where needed for strategic reasons. At one time, establishing coaling stations for naval ships was important. During the [[Cold War]], the [[United States]] and the [[Soviet Union]] established military bases where they could within their respective spheres of influence, and actively sought influence where needed. More recently, the [[War on Terror]] has resulted in overseas military bases being established in the [[Middle East]].\n\nWhilst the overall number of overseas military bases has fallen since 1945, [[France]], [[Russia]], the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United States]] still possess or utilize a substantial number. Smaller numbers of overseas military bases are operated by [[Australia]], [[China]], [[India]], [[Italy]], and [[Turkey]].\n\nThe United States is the largest operator of military bases abroad, with 38 \"named bases\"<ref group=note>What are here termed \"named bases\" are the bases listed in section X: \"Personnel Data from DMDC\", i.e. excluding that table's rows labelled \"Other\", in the 2015 DoD Base Structure Report.</ref> having active duty, national guard, reserve or civilian personnel as of September 30, 2014. Its largest, in terms of personnel, was [[Ramstein AB]] in Germany, with almost 9,200 personnel.<ref name=BSR-2015-PERS>{{cite web|url=http://www.kritisches-netzwerk.de/sites/default/files/us_department_of_defense_-_base_structure_report_fiscal_year_2015_baseline_-_as_of_30_sept_2014_-_a_summary_of_the_real_property_inventory_-_206_pages.pdf |title=Department of Defense / Base Structure Report / FY 2015 Baseline |accessdate=October 10, 2016 }}</ref><ref group=note>The 2015 U.S. Base Structure Report gives 587 overseas ''sites'', but ''sites'' are merely real property at a distinct geographical location, and multiple sites may belong to one installation (page DoD-3). For example, the Garmisch, Germany \"named base\" with its 72 personnel has eight distinct sites large enough to be listed in the Army's Individual Service Inventory list: Artillery Kaserne, Breitenau Skeet Range, Garmisch Family Housing, Garmish Golf Course, General Abrams Hotel And Disp, Hausberg Ski Area, Oberammergau NATO School, and Sheridan Barracks (listed in Army-15 to Army-17). These range in size from Ramstein AB with 9,188 active, guard/reserve, and civilian personnel down to Worms, which has just one civilian.</ref>\n<!--- The United States... as many as 662 sites in 38 countries in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Base Structure Report|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/2009/090930_fy10_baseline_dod_bsr.pdf|accessdate=3 April 2016|agency=U.S. Department of Defense|page=9}}</ref> --->\n\n==Australia==\n* {{flagu|Malaysia}} \u2013 [[RMAF Butterworth|Butterworth Air Base]] is used for Australia's commitment to the [[Five Power Defence Arrangements]] (FPDA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.airforce.gov.au/about-us/bases/overseas/rmaf-base-butterworth|title=RMAF Base Butterworth|work=Royal Australian Air Force|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref> In addition, the [[Australian Army]] maintains an infantry company (designated [[Rifle Company Butterworth]]) at Butterworth for training purposes.\n* {{flagu|United Arab Emirates}} \u2013 [[Al Minhad Air Base]] used for Australian operations in the Middle East.\n\n==China==\n* {{flagu|Afghanistan}} \u2013 China has an unofficial military presence in the [[Wakhan Corridor]], since approximately 2016.<ref name=\"WapoFeb18\">{{cite news |first=Gerry |last=Shih |first2=Anton |last2=Troianovski |first3=Yuan |last3=Wang |first4=Dan |last4=Lamothe |date=February 18, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |title=In Central Asia\u2019s forbidding highlands, a quiet newcomer: Chinese troops |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/in-central-asias-forbidding-highlands-a-quiet-newcomer-chinese-troops/2019/02/18/78d4a8d0-1e62-11e9-a759-2b8541bbbe20_story.html}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Cambodia}} \u2013 China has gained access to the [[Ream Naval Base]] in [[Cambodia]]. Currently, the Cambodian government has denied and disputed the presence of the existence of such base.<ref>[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ream_Naval_Base&action=edit&section=2 The Ramifications of China\u2019s Reported Naval Base in Cambodia], World Politics Review, 5 August 2019</ref>\n* {{flagu|Djibouti}} \u2013 [[Chinese People's Liberation Army Support Base in Djibouti]]\n* {{flagu|Myanmar}} \u2013 China has a naval intelligence base in the [[Great Coco Island]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=https://www.globalsecurity.org/intell/world/china/coco.htm}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Tajikistan}} \u2013 China has a military base in [[Tajikistan]], since approximately 2016.<ref name=\"WapoFeb18\"/>\n\n==France==\n{{Main|Overseas military bases of France}}\n* {{flagu|Djibouti}} \u2013 Les forces fran\u00e7aises stationn\u00e9es \u00e0 Djibouti (FFDj)<ref name=\"Lesforcesfran\u00e7aises\">{{cite web|title=Les forces fran\u00e7aises pr\u00e9positionn\u00e9es|url=http://www.defense.gouv.fr/content/download/466302/7428994/file/DOSSIER%20-%20Forces%20pr%C3%A9positionn%C3%A9es.pdf|publisher=defense.gouv.fr|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=europarl>{{cite journal|title=The Status and Location of the Military Installations of the Member States of the European Union |journal=Policy Department External Policies|date=February 2009|pages=13\u201314|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meetdocs/2004_2009/documents/dv/sede300309studype407004_/SEDE300309StudyPE407004_en.pdf|accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|United Arab Emirates}} \u2013 Forces de pr\u00e9sence aux Emirats arabes unis<ref name=\"Lesforcesfran\u00e7aises\"/><ref name=europarl/>\n* {{flagu|Ivory Coast}} \u2013 Les forces fran\u00e7aises en C\u00f4te d'Ivoire (FFCI)<ref name=\"Lesforcesfran\u00e7aises\"/><ref name=europarl/>\n* {{flagu|Gabon}} \u2013 Les \u00e9l\u00e9ments fran\u00e7ais au Gabon (EFG)<ref name=\"Lesforcesfran\u00e7aises\"/><ref name=europarl/>\n* {{flagu|Senegal}} \u2013 Les \u00e9l\u00e9ments fran\u00e7ais au S\u00e9n\u00e9gal (EFS)<ref name=\"Lesforcesfran\u00e7aises\"/><ref name=europarl/>\n* {{flagu|Germany}} \u2013 [[Franco-German Brigade]] in [[M\u00fcllheim]] and a [[Eurocopter Tiger]] training center at [[Fa\u00dfberg Air Base]]\n* {{flagu|Lebanon}} \u2013 [[Dayr Kifa Air Force Base]] as part of [[United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon]]\n* {{flagu|Chad}} \u2013 [[N'Djamena International Airport#French military base|N'Djamena Air Force Base]] as part of [[Operation Barkhane]]\n* {{flagu|Niger}} \u2013 [[Diori Hamani International Airport#Base A\u00e9rienne 101|Niamey Air Force Base]] as part of [[Operation Barkhane]]\n* {{flagu|Syria}} \u2013 At least three bases near [[Koban\u00ee]], [[Sarrin]] and [[Ayn Issa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syria.tv/content/%D9%87%D9%84-%D8%B4%D8%A7%D9%87%D8%AF%D8%AA-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%86%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%85%D9%86-%D9%82%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%9F-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%83-%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%8A%D9%84%D9%87%D8%A7 |script-title=ar:\u0647\u0644 \u0634\u0627\u0647\u062f\u062a \u0645\u0648\u0627\u0642\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0648\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0631\u0646\u0633\u064a\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0633\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0627 \u0645\u0646 \u0642\u0628\u0644\u061f|website=syria.tv|language=Arabic|date=20 May 2018}}</ref> as part of [[Op\u00e9ration Chammal]]\n*{{flagu|Iraq}} \u2013 Forces in [[Baghdad Governorate|Baghdad]] as part of [[Op\u00e9ration Chammal]]\n\n==Germany==\n* {{flagu|France}} \u2013 [[Franco-German Brigade]] in [[Illkirch-Graffenstaden]] near [[Strasbourg]] and a [[Eurocopter Tiger]] training center in [[Le Cannet-des-Maures]]\n* {{flagu|United States}} \u2013 Germany has aircraft training facilities at [[Holloman Air Force Base]] in New Mexico and at [[Naval Air Station Pensacola]] in Florida. (training base)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.luftwaffe.de/portal/a/luftwaffe/!ut/p/c4/NYtNC8IwEET_0W7ioYI3xQ_0oHjS9rY2MYSmSdlu7MUfb3JwBh4Dj8EOSyN9vCPxKVLAJ7a937wWCAskdkB5DjCYlOcy38Lk8FFPxkKfopVKsVF8oWOSxDAlllBNZi4GvMFW6f1ONeof_V0futP9stLN-Xq84TSO2x9rK0eT/|title=2nd German Air Force Training Squadron USA in Pensacola, Florida|language=German|access-date=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Greece==\n* {{flagu|Cyprus}} \u2013 [[Hellenic Force in Cyprus]]\n\n==India==\n{{main | List of Indian Air Force stations | List of Indian Navy bases }}\n\nThe [[Indian Armed Forces]], including [[Special Forces of India]], operate several bases and stations:\n\n* {{flagu|Tajikistan}} \u2013 [[Farkhor Air Base]] is an Air Force base operated by the [[Indian Air Force]] and [[Tajik Air Force]]. It is located near [[Farkhar|Farkhor]] town, 130&nbsp;km from [[Dushanbe]]. With this base India became the 4th country after the US, Russia and Germany to have a military base in [[Central Asia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurasiantimes.com/farkhor-air-base-india-tajikistan/|title=After Farkhor Air Base, India Tajikistan Set for More Security Pacts|last=Times|first=EurAsian|date=2018-05-03|website=EurAsian Times: Latest Asian, Middle-East, EurAsian, Indian News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/defence/india-renews-interest-in-running-its-first-foreign-military-base-in-tajikistan/132454/|title=India renews interest in running its first foreign military base in Tajikistan|last=Dutta|first=Sujan|date=2018-10-11|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n*{{flagu|Bhutan}} \u2013 The [[Indian Military Training Team]] (IMTRAT) is permanently stationed in western Bhutan.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yOIjCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT292&dq=IMTRAT&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi88Irui_LZAhVRwFkKHWv6CrgQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q=IMTRAT&f=false|title=A Political and Economic Dictionary of South Asia|last=Schottli|first=Jivanta|last2=Mitra|first2=Subrata K.|last3=Wolf|first3=Siegried|date=2015-05-08|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135355753|language=en}}</ref>\n*{{Flag|Nepal}} - [[India]] shares a very strong relation with Nepal and the [[Indian Army]] also provides security to Nepal, with a Security claim on the factor that any attack on Nepal would be considered as an attack on India. The [[Indian Air Force]] maintains an airstrip in [[Surkhet District|Surkhet]], in Nepal which will provide support to [[Nepal]] in case of any incoming airborne threats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defencedirecteducation.com/military-base-indian-outside-india/|title=10 Indian Military bases outside India|last=|first=|date=|website=Defence Direct Education|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*{{flagu|Maldives}} \u2013 Coastal Surveillance Radar station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://topyaps.com/india-military-overseas-base/|title=These 5 Overseas Military Bases Speaks Volumes About India's Growing Military Footprint|date=2016-11-28|website=TopYaps|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Madagascar}} \u2013 A listening post and a radar facility in northern Madagascar.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xllmBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA128&dq=madagascar+indian+radar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_-oHYjPLZAhVltlkKHUvZAiEQ6AEILDAB#v=onepage&q=madagascar%20indian%20radar&f=false|title=India's Rise as an Asian Power: Nation, Neighborhood, and Region|last=Gordon|first=A. D. D.|last2=Gordon|first2=Sandy|date=2014-08-05|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=9781626160743|language=en}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Mauritius}} \u2013 A coast surveillance radar system deployed and maintained by India.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2015/03/india-unveils-new-coastal-surveillance-radar-network/|title=India Unveils New Coastal Surveillance Radar Network|last=Diplomat|first=Ankit Panda, The|work=The Diplomat|access-date=2018-03-17|language=en-US}}</ref>&nbsp;As of June 2017, the current status of all these projects is unclear.<ref>{{cite web|title=Agalega and the lndia-China control of the Indian Ocean|url=https://www.lemauricien.com/article/agalega-and-lndia-china-control-indian-ocean/|website=.lemauricien.com|publisher=Le Mauricien|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Seychelles}} \u2013 A coast surveillance radar system deployed and maintained by India.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.seychellesnewsagency.com/articles/4828/New%20coastal%20radar%20system%20means%20better%20safeguards%20for%20Seychelles,%20official%20says|title=New coastal radar system means better safeguards for Seychelles, official says|access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Oman}} \u2013 A listening post at [[Ras al Hadd]] and berthing rights for the [[Indian Navy]] at Mascat naval base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://closewar.com/2013/03/01/indian-listening-station-in-oman-monitoring-pakistans-naval-communications/|title=Indian Listening Station In Oman Monitoring Pakistan\u2019s Naval Communications|date=2013-03-01|website=CloseWar.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> An establishment at [[Duqm]] for the [[Indian Air Force]] and the [[Indian Navy]]. Duqm had previously served as a port for the [[INS Mumbai|''INS Mumbai'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-gets-access-to-strategic-oman-port-for-military-use-chabahar-gwadar-in-sight-5061573/|title=India gets access to strategic Oman port Duqm for military use, Chabahar-Gwadar in sight|date=2018-02-13|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n*{{flagu|Iran}} \u2013 India has built a port and operates it at [[Chabahar]] for better access to Iran, Afghanistan and other central Asian states. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-takes-over-operations-of-part-of-chabahar-port-in-iran/articleshow/67424219.cms?from=mdr|title=India takes over operations of part of Chabahar Port in Iran|date=2019-01-07|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Djibouti}} \u2013 India shares the maritime assets of Japan at Djibouti under mutual sharing pact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurasiantimes.com/india-set-to-operate-massive-military-base-in-djibouti-with-japan/|title=India Set To Operate Massive Military (Naval) Base in Djibouti with Japan|last=Times|first=EurAsian|date=2018-10-17|website=EurAsian Times: Latest Asian, Middle-East, EurAsian, Indian News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Myanmar}} \u2013 India is building a port in [[Sittwe]] for better transposition of goods to its northeast and for listening Chinese activities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/india-all-set-to-take-over-ops-in-myanmars-sittwe-port-after-chabahar/articleshow/67437859.cms|title=India all set to take over ops in Myanmar's Sittwe Port after Chabahar|last=Chaudhury|first=Dipanjan Roy|date=2019-01-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Qatar}} \u2013 India maintains berth rights and right to station its troops under mutual assistance pact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/archive/india-qatar-ink-key-defence-pact/383907/|title=India, Qatar ink key defence pact|date=2008-11-11|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n*{{Flag|Vietnam}} - Both India and Vietnam shares a strong military relationship, as India is also considered to as one of the major Defence and Strategic partners of Vietnam. thus, Vietnam has also invited India to maintain the hold of its Naval presence in the [[South China Sea|South China Sea region]] and has granted allowance to India to maintain its Air and Naval Base at the [[Cam Ranh Bay]], in Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defencedirecteducation.com/military-base-indian-outside-india/|title=10 Military bases outside India.|last=Education|first=Defence Direct|date=|website=Defence Direct Education|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*{{Flag|Mozambique}}- India and Mozambique have strategic relations dating back to 1986. The Indian Navy had and also plays a very important role since the 2003 African Union Summit and the World Economic Forum Summit, as it had taken a consistent charge for Sea Security of Mozambique. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defencedirecteducation.com/military-base-indian-outside-india/|title=10 Indian Military bases Outside India|last=|first=|date=|website=Defence Direct Education|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Iran==\n* {{flagu|Syria}} \u2013 A military base near [[Al-Kiswah]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-41945189|title=Iran building missile factories in Syria and Lebanon - Netanyahu|website=BBC News|date=28 August 2017}}</ref> [[Abu Kamal]] and several facilities in 3 different [[Governorates of Syria|governorates]]<ref>{{cite web|ur