flagu|United States}} \u2013 [[Sheppard Air Force Base]] (training base),<ref name=\"Messaggero\"/> [[Eglin Air Force Base]] (training base)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.timesrecordnews.com/story/news/local/2018/07/31/sheppard-afb-hosts-change-command-italian-senior-official/873662002/|title=Sheppard AFB hosts change of command for Italian senior official|website=Times Record News|date=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Japan==\n* {{flagu|Djibouti}} \u2013 [[Japan Self-Defense Force Base Djibouti]]<ref>[https://www.chathamhouse.org/publications/papers/view/190835 Djibouti: Changing Influence in the Horn\u2019s Strategic Hub], chathamhouse.org, David Styan, April 2013 (\"''Having temporarily used US facilities, a Japanese base, situated close to [[Camp Lemonnier]], opened in July 2011. Around 600 members of its Maritime Self-Defence Forces rotate between Japan\u2019s naval vessels operating from the port of Djibouti and the camp. Naval units protecting Japanese shipping in the region had operated out of the US base prior to 2011. Japan is reported to pay an annual rent of $30 million for the facilities, similar to the sums paid for either of the far larger US and French bases. This has led to an expansion of Japan\u2019s civilian aid programme to Djibouti, which has also become a hub for wider development activities in the Horn by the Japan International Cooperation Agency.''\")</ref>\n\n==Netherlands==\n* {{flagu|United States}} \u2013 [[Tucson Air National Guard Base|Netherlands Detachment Tucson Arizona]] (training base)<ref>https://airforcesmonthly.keypublishing.com/2018/04/05/dutch-viper-training-in-arizona/</ref>\n\n==Pakistan==\n{{Main|Pakistan Armed Forces deployments}}\n* {{flagu|Saudi Arabia}} \u2013 1,180 personnel in [[Tabuk, Saudi Arabia|Tabuk]] and other bases in permanent training and advisory roles, under a 1982 agreement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1175231|title=Troops already in Saudi Arabia, says minister|work=Dawn|date=11 April 2015|accessdate=8 June 2017|quote=Our troops are already present in Tabuk and some other cities of Saudi Arabia.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1328531|title=Raheel leaves for Riyadh to command military alliance|work=Dawn|date=22 April 2017|accessdate=8 June 2017|first=Baqir Sajjad|last=Syed|quote=Pakistan already has 1,180 troops in Saudi Arabia under a 1982 bilateral agreement. The deployed troops are mostly serving there in training and advisory capacity.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.com/en/examining-saudi-pakistani-ties-in-changing-geopolitics/a-19512946|title=Examining Saudi-Pakistani ties in changing geopolitics|work=Deutsche Welle|first=Shamil|last=Shams|date=30 August 2016|accessdate=8 June 2017|quote=However, security experts say that being an ally of Saudi Arabia, Pakistan is part of a security cooperation agreement under which about 1,000 Pakistani troops are performing an \"advisory\" role to Riyadh and are stationed in Saudi Arabia and other Gulf countries.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1049472/ambiguity-persists-pakistan-still-clueless-about-role-in-saudi-coalition-front-page/|title=Pakistan still clueless about role in Saudi coalition|work=The Express Tribune|date=18 February 2016|accessdate=8 June 2017|first=Riazul|last=Haq|quote=Aziz said military cooperation between Pakistan and Saudi Arabia was nearly four decades\u2019 old, and around 1,000 Pakistani military officials were always present in the kingdom.}}</ref>\n\n==Russia==\n{{Main|List of Russian military bases abroad}} \n* {{flagu|Armenia}} \u2013 [[Russian 102nd Military Base]] in [[Gyumri]] and the Russian 3624th Airbase in [[Erebuni Airport]] near [[Yerevan]]\n* {{flagu|Belarus}} \u2013 [[Hantsavichy Radar Station]]; [[Vileyka VLF transmitter|Vileyka naval communication centre]]\n* {{flagu|Georgia}} \u2013 Russian 4th Military Base in the [[International recognition of Abkhazia and South Ossetia|disputed]] [[frozen conflict]] regions o